{{third-party|date=February 2014}} The '''Humanities Indicators''' is a project of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] that equips researchers and policymakers, universities, foundations, museums, libraries, humanities councils and other public institutions with statistical tools for answering basic questions about primary and secondary humanities education, undergraduate and graduate education in the [[humanities]], the humanities workforce, levels and sources of program funding, public understanding and impact of the humanities, and other areas of concern in the humanities community.<ref>[http://chronicle.com/article/First-National-Picture-of/1437 ''Chronicle of Higher Education'', "First National Picture of Trends in the Humanities Is Unveiled"].</ref><ref>[http://www.humanitiesindicators.org/content/system/inTheNews.aspx Indicators in the News].</ref>
Data from the Humanities Indicators has been widely discussed in recent conversations about a "crisis in the humanities", in light of a national decline in the number of college majors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/06/05/analysis-finds-significant-drop-humanities-majors-gains-liberal-arts-degrees|title=Humanities Majors Drop|last=Jaschik|first=Scott|date=June 5, 2017|work=Inside Higher Ed|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/liberal-arts-majors-are-a-dying-breed-2017-06-05|title=Liberal arts majors are a dying breed|last=Berman|first=Jillian|date=July 30, 2017|work=MarketWatch|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> To address questions about the workforce outcomes of humanities graduates (which are often cited as playing a role in the falling number of majors as of 2015), the Indicators issued [https://www.amacad.org/multimedia/pdfs/publications/researchpapersmonographs/HI_Workforce-2018.pdf ''The State of the Humanities 2018: Graduates in the Workforce & Beyond''], which examined not only their employment and earnings relative to other fields, but also graduates’ satisfaction with their work after graduation and their lives more generally. The data reveal that despite disparities in median earnings, humanities majors are quite similar to graduates from other fields with respect to their ''perceived'' well-being. The report was widely cited in the media as an important intervention in the discussion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/education-lab/report-busts-myth-of-unemployable-humanities-grads/|title=Report busts myth of unemployable humanities grads|last=Long|first=Katherine|date=February 12, 2018|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/02/07/study-finds-humanities-majors-land-jobs-and-are-happy-them|title=Shocker: Humanities Grads Gainfully Employed and Happy|last=Jaschik|first=Scott|date=February 7, 2018|work=Inside Higher Ed|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Over-Time-Humanities-Grads/242461|title=Over Time, Humanities Grads Close the Pay Gap With Professional Peers|last=Carlson|first=Scott|date=February 7, 2018|work=Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=|archive-url=|archivedate=|dead-url=}}</ref>
